english:
  title: The Root of Righteousness
  author: Seong Hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The venerable one's virtue shines through heaven and earth,
    A mirror of water in the breast—clear, never murky.
    Unmoving, always still, the source remains crystalline;
    Where light strikes, it blazes forth in brilliant sparks.

    Descending to the turbid world, yet unstained by its dust,
    Infinite beings rely upon this root of goodness.
    Gwanaksan rises high, pressing down the thick earth;
    Gwanaksa, ancient temple, makes the mountain its gate.
    The mountain gate lies rough with moss-covered stone;
    Vines and ivy bar the touch of common hands.
    Lush trees burst forth in spring's abundance,
    While rocks jut high as if dragons were crouching there.
    In this luminous realm, no clamor disturbs the peace—
    Palm leaves turned slowly in quiet leisure.

    This body sustained by earth receives the sovereign's grace,
    Yet staff in hand, I must descend to the dusty world.
    The mountain empties, the chamber stills, the bare walls stand bare.
    The stone crane cries, the forest monkey grieves—
    But the mountain spirit claps his hands and laughs:
    "Why bind yourself in such narrow constraint?

    The great temple rises like Jetavana itself,
    With jeweled halls and banners bright arrayed,
    Lamps lit in rows, ritual standards unfurled.
    Scholars debate the sutras, their names renowned—
    Fame spreads beneath the honored roof,
    Yet the meditative heart wearies of this clamor.

    Autumn wind stirs wings that long to soar;
    Brilliance and acclaim hold no sway here.
    Let me cast this body back to the source,
    Where neither sorrow nor joy, neither debt nor grace exists—
    The vast wisdom of mind, the great way's original spring,
    Entering the non-dual, beyond all words and names.

    The old meditation hall, the pine and moon still fair,
    While cool springs rush to cleanse what must be cleansed.
    The mountain spirit welcomes me as brother,
    And monkeys and cranes move in harmony.
    In one still room the morning sun ascends;
    In Baksan's incense, smoke rises clear and warm.
    Gazing down at the dusty realm below, clouds gather thick;
    Wild trees like shepherd's purse encircle the lonely village.
    Mountain high, the person high, the way profound—
    I swear never to forget this joy.

    Shame on this muddled, darkened life of mine!
    Wherever profit leads, the soul secretly withers.
    A lifetime spent rushing east and west,
    Lashed by greed and agitation's burning heat.
    I take refuge in the dharma, seeking wondrous salvation—
    How can a quail grasp the wings of the great Peng?

    With whitened hair on the meditation bench, wind scattering free,
    I long to discuss the sublime doctrine of the three vehicles,
    Yet this body drowns in the red dust, trapped like a louse in a seam,
    Turning aside to gaze uselessly at the clear river below.

    Written in the seventh month of the Renxu year, at evening's fall,
    From the pavilion of the Study of Investigating Things.
  footnotes:
    - 'Gwanaksan (관악산) and Gwanaksa (관악사): A mountain and its ancient temple near Seoul, representing the natural and spiritual realm the poet seeks.'
    - 'Jetavana: The famous Buddhist monastery in ancient India, here symbolizing an ideal sacred space.'
    - 'The ''non-dual, beyond all words and names'' (불이 무명언): A reference to Buddhist philosophy transcending dualistic thought.'
    - 'Baksan incense (박산 향로): A reference to a famous censer, evoking refined spiritual atmosphere.'
    - 'The three vehicles (삼승): Buddhist doctrine referring to different paths of enlightenment.'
    - 'Renxu year (임술년): Likely 1562, establishing the poem''s historical context.'
